{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633580"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:55:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:55:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17485"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17485"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10175"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70722"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10175"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17485"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56188"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5363"},{"type":"tags","id":"5370"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23782"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70722"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPopulation screening programmes aim to detect disease early to improve health outcomes. However, these programmes can also have unintended consequences.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a potential harm of population screening programmes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased healthcare costs from additional diagnostic testing","Psychological distress from waiting for test results","Overdiagnosis of clinically insignificant disease","Detection of false positive results leading to unnecessary interventions","False reassurance from false negative results"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most significant harm of screening programmes is \u003Cstrong\u003Edetection of false positive results leading to unnecessary interventions\u003C/strong\u003E. False positives can cause psychological distress and lead to additional invasive testing, which carries its own risks and costs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other genuine harms of screening, but are less significant:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased healthcare costs from additional diagnostic testing\u003C/strong\u003E is a real concern but is secondary to the direct patient impact of false positives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychological distress from waiting for test results\u003C/strong\u003E affects many participants but is usually temporary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOverdiagnosis of clinically insignificant disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an important issue but affects fewer people than false positives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFalse reassurance from false negative results\u003C/strong\u003E can delay diagnosis but occurs less frequently than false positives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther potential harms of screening include resource allocation issues, opportunity costs, and the burden of labelling someone with a diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Screening tests can produce false positive results which may lead to unnecessary anxiety and further testing.","The positive predictive value of a screening test is lower when the condition being screened for is rare in the population.","Overdiagnosis occurs when screening detects disease 